Here is an example of how to create a simple search bar using PHP:

**index.php**
```php
<?php
// Connect to database (assuming MySQL)
$servername = "localhost";
$username = "root";
$password = "";
$dbname = "example";

$conn = new mysqli($servername, $username, $password, $dbname);

if ($conn->connect_error) {
    die("Connection failed: " . $conn->connect_error);
}

// Define search query
$searchQuery = $_GET['search'];

// Query database to retrieve matching results
$sql = "SELECT * FROM example_table WHERE column_name LIKE '%$searchQuery%'";
$result = $conn->query($sql);

?>
```
**search_form.php**
```php
<?php include 'index.php'; ?>

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Search Results</title>
    <style>
        /* Add some basic styling for the search form */
        #search-form {
            width: 50%;
            margin: 20px auto;
            padding: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2);
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <form id="search-form" action="<?php echo $_SERVER['PHP_SELF']; ?>" method="GET">
        <input type="text" name="search" placeholder="Search...">
        <button type="submit">Search</button>
    </form>

    <?php if ($result->num_rows > 0) { ?>
        <!-- Display search results -->
        <table>
            <tr>
                <th>Column Name</th>
                <th>Result</th>
            </tr>
            <?php while ($row = $result->fetch_assoc()) { ?>
                <tr>
                    <td><?php echo $row['column_name']; ?></td>
                    <td><?php echo $row['result']; ?></td>
                </tr>
            <?php } ?>
        </table>
    <?php } else { ?>
        <!-- Display no results message -->
        <p>No results found.</p>
    <?php } ?>

</body>
</html>
```
**How it works:**

1. The user submits a search query through the `search_form.php` page.
2. The form is submitted to the same page, which processes the search query using PHP.
3. The search query is then used to construct an SQL query that searches for matching results in the database.
4. The result of the query is retrieved and displayed on the same page.

**Note:**

* This example uses a very basic form of searching (i.e., `%$searchQuery%`). You may want to use more advanced search techniques, such as using indexes or full-text search functionality.
* Make sure to escape user input properly to prevent SQL injection attacks.
* This is just a simple example and you should adapt it to your specific needs.

Also, make sure that the `column_name` in the `$sql` query is replaced with the actual column name of the table you're searching.

